Figure: High-level system architecture for the smart irrigation system. Crucial Technical Implementation (Credit: Joseph Wong &amp; Jonathan Chua Jie Xin) <p> A. Environmental Feedback and Automated Response This logic enables the system to automatically adjust water flow based on rain detection and water level, ensuring efficient irrigation: <p><pre><code>if (PORTBbits.RB1 == 0) { // rain detected
    SetDutyCycleTo(5.0, Period); // Reduce water flow
} else {
    SetDutyCycleTo(12.3, Period); // Normal flow
}
ADCON0bits.GO = 1; // Start ADC conversion
while(ADCON0bits.GO == 1); // Wait for conversion
if (ADRESH &gt; HIGH) { // Water level high
    pump();
}
</code></pre> This snippet demonstrates real-time adaptation to environmental conditions using sensor feedback and automated actuation. B. Pump Control Function The core actuation logic, which sequentially activates three pumps to distribute water efficiently:</p> <p><pre><code>void pump(void){
    PORTDbits.RD1 = 1;
    PORTBbits.RB2 = 0; delay(1000); PORTBbits.RB2 = 1;
    PORTBbits.RB3 = 0; delay(1000); PORTBbits.RB3 = 1;
    PORTBbits.RB6 = 0; delay(1000); PORTBbits.RB6 = 1;
    PORTDbits.RD1 = 0;
}
</code></pre> This function is responsible for the physical actuation of the irrigation pumps, ensuring even water distribution across the system. </p>
